SIMPLE: stum
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stum
<hw>Stum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[D. <ets>stom</ets> must,
new wort, properly, dumb; cf. F. <ets>vin muet</ets> stum. Cf.
<er>Stammer</er>, <er>Stoom</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Unfermented
grape juice or wine, often used to raise fermentation in dead or vapid
wines; must.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let our wines, without mixture of <qex>stum</qex>, be all
fine.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And with thy <qex>stum</qex> ferment their fainting cause.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Wine revived by new fermentation, reulting from the
admixture of must.</def> <rj><au>Hudibras.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stum</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stum
<hw>Stum</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Stummed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Stumming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To renew, as wine, by mixing
must with it and raising a new fermentation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We <qex>stum</qex> our wines to renew their spirits.</q>
<rj><qau>Floyer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stumble</ent>⟦br⟧
